This analysis considers both the frequency of real-world triggering events contributing to childhood fears and the structured assessments utilized in evaluating pediatric anxiety disorders. The evidence suggests that while various forms of specific phobia exist, zoophobia appears to be notably more prevalent based on its connection to ubiquitous environmental factors impacting young individuals' emotional landscapes during their formative years. Thus, given this rationale rooted in direct experiential contexts combined with standardized evaluations delineating key indicators for diagnosis and management, zoophobia stands out as the most probable candidate for representing the 'most common phobia' among children. \boxed{A}
